<div id="comment_status_49553" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_49553" class="oneline">

	<div id="comment_top_49553" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			
			<h4><a id="comment_link_49553" name="comment_link_49553" href="//use.perl.org/comments.pl?sid=32687&amp;cid=49553" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(49553)">Re:</a>
			
			<span id="comment_score_49553" class="score">(<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 49553); return false">Score:1</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			by
			<a href="//use.perl.org/~Yanick/">Yanick (3196)</a>
			
			
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_49553"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_49553"><p>It's very similar indeed. The big difference is that T::P::S extracts the code to test directly from the pod, whereas with T::I you have to explicitly add the test code. In other words, T::I don't do any dark voodoo magic with the pod, it just deal with files that contains code, pod <i>and</i> tests.</p><span class="substr"> </span><p>For example, with T::I you'd have to write:</p><blockquote><div><p> <code>
=head2 Foo<br>
<br>
That's how you do it:<br>
<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;# will set $x to 'baz'<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;my $x = bar( $y ); <br>
</code></p> </div></blockquote><blockquote><div><p> <code>
=begin testing<br>
my $x = bar( $y ); <br>
is $x =&gt; 'baz';<br>
=end tes</code></p></div></blockquote></div>
		
	
	</div>
	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_49553"></div>

</div>


